The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, April 18: India proposes to bring changes in the domestic law enabling it to protect its industries against import surges through quantitative restrictions . The move comes nine years after the country was forced to remove quantitative restrictions on imports under WTO. The standing committee of Parliament has more or less approved a provision in a bill to amend the foreign trade (development and regulation) act.                             
	 New Delhi, April 18: The Institute of Chartered Accountants of India (ICAI) has sought details of the tie-ups of audit companies with global firms to check surrogate practices. The decision to seek details from CA firms, especially those associated with the Big 4  PWC, Ernst amp; Young, KPMG and Deloitte  follows a report by an ICAI committee on the multi-crore Satyam scam.                            
	 Mumbai, April 18: Remittances by Indian expatriates rose over $1 billion to $27.51 billion (around Rs 1,22,420 crore) during April-September 2009, unfazed by the global financial meltdown, an RBI survey has said. Remittances stood at $26.37 billion during the corresponding period of the previous year.                             
	 Washington, April 18: Increased protectionist measures by various countries could hamper global economic recovery and drag down future growth, IMF economists have said.                             
	 Mumbai, April 18: Gruh Finance, the home loan arm of mortgage lender HDFC, plans to raise around Rs 100 crore of tier II (equity) capital by issuing non-convertible debentures, most likely in the second quarter of this fiscal.                             
	 New Delhi, April 18: The countrys handicrafts exports grew over 60 per cent in February on account of the growing demand in major global markets such as the US and Europe.                            
	 New Delhi, April 18: Indian capital markets can grow three-fold by 2020 if reforms to increase retail participation, reduce cost of trade and enhance investment by pension funds are initiated, a study by Ficci and Mckinsey amp; Company, said.                                                                                                                          
